There =will come a time that you will have too much of a specific fluid and you will need to dump it.  In mose cases this will occur first with waste water from your ore processing line.  Greg Tech 6 has a solution for you.  The Ender Garbage Bin 5000 (Well it just called the Ender Garbage Bin).

The bin will take any fluid and send it into the ender void.  All uou need is an Eye of Ender and some obsidian plates, and 3 iron plates.  You will get the obsidian plates by putting an iron bucket of lava in you crucible (you may need to heat it a bit to get the lava molten again).  Then just pour your plates.  Finally you get the Eye of Ender by getting an Ender Pearl from an Enderman and a Tiny Blaze Power.  You can craft 2 tiny Blaze powers from one rod by hand or you can get 2 small blaze dusts bu using a shredder.
§a
To ocmplete the quest craft:
1 Ender Garbage Bin

betterquesting:10.name:8: Wrap It Up, I'll Take It!
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
So what od you do if you want to moke an tem barrel that is full of stuff.  If you pick it up with an axe, all the items will dump on the ground.  Well, you can wrap the item barrel in tape and then you can move it.  All you need is some paper and glue and you will have yourself a roll of tape.  Once you have the iten barrel in a new location, you use your knife to remove the tabe so you can once again retrieve or place items in that barrel.
§a
To complete this quest craft:
1 roll of tape (paper)

As you are setting up your processing lines, you will need to have pipes that can pass acids without disolving.  This is where stainlesss steel pipes com in handy.  So lets make some small stainless steel pipes.
§a
To complete the quest craft:
4 Small Stainless Steel Fluid Pipes.

The cheap wooden item barrels are very limited in how much they can store.  By using iron, you can double the storage capacity per barrel.  You will need some treated wood and 2 long iron rods.
§a
To complete this quest c;raft:
1 Wooden Item Barrel (iron)

As you develop your base, you will discover that you will have some extra fluids that you don't know what to do.  Well some of these fluids can be burned in burning boxes.  The first will be Creosol.  So to use the fluids all you need are fluid burning boxes.
§9§b
Note:  There are dense versions of the burning boxes that will output higher amounts of heat but will use the fuel much quicker.
§f§a
To complete this quest craft:
1 Bronze, Steel or Invar Fluid Burning Box

As you continue to develop your base you will come across gasses that you don't know what to do with them.  Some of these gasses are burnable like Hydrogen, Butane, Methane, etc.  There are also natural gas springs where you can catch the gas and bring it back to you base to use as fuel.  In order to use gasses as fuel, you will need a gas burning box.
§b
Note:  There are dense versions of the burning boxes that will output higher amounts of heat but will use the fuel much quicker.
§f§a
To complete the quest craft:
1 Bronze, Invar, or Steel Gas Burning Box

You may need a tank to store your acids so you can move them around or to have a small reservoir of the acid.  In order to store acids, you will need a drum that will not disolve.  Currently you have stainless steel and that will work.
§a
To complete this quest craft:
1 Stainless Stell Drum

Now we have sulfur trioxide, which we can now mix it with some water and we get sulfuric acid!

All you need to do is pipe over the sulfer trioxide and water and then pipe out the sulfuric acid.  You can use a bronze turbine as the mixer only need 16RU to make the sulfuric acid.  The pipes that you use to pipe over the water and sulfur trioxide are up to you.  Bronze or rubber will work.

You will need the following machines:
1 Bronze burnign Box [any type]
1 Bronze Boiler
1 Bronze Turbine
1 Bronze Mixer
some small bornze/invar pipes for gas input
some small stainless steel pipes for output
§6§e
Warning:  Be careful with the fluid output from your mixer.  make sure the pipes and drum can handle acids before using them.  Hint:  wonder why stainless steel is in this tab?
§f§6§7§8§9§a§b§c§d§e§d§e§f§k§f§6§b§a§6
Mixer Recipe:
1000L Sulfur Trioxide + 750L Water => [Mixer 16RU/t] =>  1750L Sulfuric Acid
§6§a
To complete the quest collect the following:
1000L Sulfuric Acid in a drum (USE STAINLESS STEEL!!)

Now that you are making acids, you will need a place to store them.  Invar and Wooden tanks will not do.  So we will need an Stainless Steel Tank.  You cna guss that we will need some Stainless Steel Walls and a Stainless Steel Valve.
§a
To complete the wquest craft:
1 Small Stainless Steel Valve
25 Small Stainless Steel Walls

betterquesting:10.name:8: It is Time for a Bath
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
We are going to need a bath to process our tungsten bearing ores so that we can get the tungsten dusts.  So lets make a bath that can handle acids.
§a
To Complete the quest craft:
1 Bath

Would you want more room to store your needed plates, rods, screws, or any other part and have it connect to your Advanced Crafting Table.  I have a deal for you.  With the cost of a few plates I offer you the Compartment Drawer.  Just craft one and place it next to your Advanced Crafting table and now you have more stoarge for your stuff with the ease of the Advanced Crafting Table crafting.
§a
To complete the quest craft:
1 Bronze, Lead, Invar or Steel Compartment Drawer.

Now it is time to set up the machines that you need to process your Tungsten bearing ores like Scheelite and wolfranite.

First you need to set up a bath that will use your Hydrocloric Acid.  This will give you the much need Tungstic Acid Dusts that you need for further processing.  You will also get Magnesium Cloride or Calcium Cloride depending on the ore you choose to process.  We will deal with these at a later time.  Just stick them in a item barrel for now. 
§6
Bath Recipe:
6 Tungsten Bearing Dust + 4000L Hydrocloric Acid => [Bath] => 3 [Mg/Li/Ca/Fe/Mn]Chloride Dust + 7 Tungstic Acid Dust
Note:  Tungsten Bearing Dusts are:  Ferberite/Huebnerite/Scheelite/Wolframite
§f
Next you will need to set up a steel dryer to dry the Tungstic Acid Dusts.  You will get Tungsten Trioxide which you will send to the mixer for further processing and distilled water that you can recycle for your boilers.  You can choose the type of steel burning box depending on what fuels you ahve available.

The final step is to set up a mixer to mix Tungsten Trioxide with Hydrogen to give you your tungsten dusts and water.  You can recycle the water or send it to an Ender Garbage Bin.  The mixer only needs a single bronze burning box, bronze boiler and bronze turbine.
§6
Mixer Recipe:
4 Tungsten Trioxide + 6000L Hydrogen Gas => Mixer 16RU/t] => 1 Tungsten Dust + 9000L Water

§a
To complete this quest assemble a processimg line for tungsten with:
1 Bath
1 Dryer
1 Bronze Mixer
7 Tungsten Dusts

The centrifuge is a very useful machine.  It can be used to separate some coplex dusts into individual element dusts.  It can also centrifuge all of that sluice juice that the sluice has been making washing your ores.  The centrifuge will give you a chance of a tinyl copper, chrome, antimony, zinc, and tin for a small amount of sluice juice.  You will end up with quite a bit of tiny stone dust.  In the newer versions of GT6 9 stone dusts actually creates gravel in stead of stone dust blocks.  The gravel can be sifted to get some useful items like flint, clay, sand, and mmilky quartz.
§b
Note:  You can use a brinze centrifuge to process the sluice juice but you will need an invar turbine and 3 steel burning boxes and boilers to do so.  Since the recipe to process sluice juice is on the edge of both the bronze and steel centrifuges, you can use a steel centrifuge and increase the speed of the steel turbine without an energy penality.
§f§a
To complete this quest craft:
1 Bronze or Steel Centrifuge

You might be aware of Greg's Bricks domn't spawn mobs but did you know Greg has dirt that you can craft to also does not spawn mobs?

He does.  So lets make some Grege Super Non Spawning Grass Blocks.
§a
To complete this quest craft:
8 of Gregs Grass Blocks (any of the 4 types)

Ever wondered how you can move some partial liquids (less than a bottle or bucket)?  You can.  You can scoop up liquids from your baths by using a measuring pot.  You can also store the liquids in a ceramic jug.  The easiest measuring pot and jug is made from clay.  Just make a clay measuring pot and clay jug and then cook them in a furnace.  The only issue is you cannot store acids or hot liquids above 2,400 K in a ceramic jug or measuring pot.
§b
Note:  For acids there are stainless steel measuring pot.  You can also use stainless steel drum for acids and high tier metal drums for hotter liquids.
§f§a
To complete this quest craft:
1 clay measuring pot
1 ceramic measuring pot (cook the clay pot in a furnace)
1 clay jug
1 ceramic jug (cook the clay jug in a furnace)

To get Aluminum, you will need alumina.  You can get alumina from washing Bauzite in a sluice.  You can also get alumina from centrifuging saphire purified ores.

Look for the following:

- Bauxite ore.  This would be a layered rock type similar to coal, lignite, and milky quartz.

- Saphire ores.  An alternate way to get alumina dusts.

-  Milky Quartz or Nether Quartz.  You will need some quartz.


Processing Path:

Look for gravel in the usual places, like near water and especially rivers. Or get flint by picking up surface stones until you find a piece, it should be quite common.

You don't need a tool to gather gravel, you can use your bare hands for now. By breaking gravel there's a 30% chance of getting flint, and no other gravel to flint crafting recipe here. So you can always place the gravel you obtained back in the world, and repeat the process until you have transformed all of it into flint.

But to speed up the process you can easily craft a shovel, of any kind, using the surface stones you find everywhere. The durability of the tool will of course depend on the material you use. 

No crafting table required. Take one of the sticks you can find all over the ground, place a stone right above it, and you'll have a shovel. If you make it with flint, even better.

§o§7§o§8§o§0§1§l§k§f§e§d§b§a§9§oNote: if you click on the knife to look the recipe in NEI, you'll get first the ones crafted with plates. This because there is a large number of materials. If you browse back to page 95 you'll see the basic flint recipe.

Making a flint knife is a priority for a couple of reasons.

You can use it as a simple but effective weapon. Being made of flint, it has a chance of setting the target on fire on a hit. If you kill an animal this way, the meat will come already cooked and ready to be eaten.

The second good reason is that you can use the knife to cut grass all around you. You'll notice that your inventory will fill with the grass item. Always pay attention to tooltips in GT6. Once you have the Grass Bale you can place it out in the world, under the light, so that after a little while it will turn into bright yellow: a dry grass bale.

§o§7§o§9§n§n§o§n§r§9§oNote: do not place the grass bale when it's raining, or too close to water, because it will get moldy and then rot.

But if you want you can merge them in a single stack, by converting to a generic stick type. This is done by placing sticks on the §llower right§l§l§l§l§m§m§n§n§o§r§o§7 §9§ocrafting slot. The output will be a standard stick.

You'll notice that scattered around the overworld are sticks and stones on top of the normal surface. You can gather both types with a right click, precisely aimed, and the corresponding item will appear in the inventory.

Surface stones are important because they signal the type of ore you can find by digging down at that location (the ore vein can be placed at any point of the Y axis, the presence of the surface stone only tells you there's the ore below, but it doesn't signal proximity). So §cBEFORE §c§c§ryou start roaming and picking everything up, it's important that every time you pick a stone, you stop and pay attention of what kind it is.

If it's a stone of a certain ore type you should create a bookmark at that location, so that you can return later to it if you need that type of resource.

Also consider that you can find both flint and coal types of stones. With flint you can proceed to the next quests and make some basic tools. With a coal stone you can immediately craft a torch.

As a suggestion: move common types of stones to your main inventory and leave some spaces free on your hotbar. This way, whenever you pick metal stones you'll immediately notice, and place a bookmark. It could also be a good idea to place these stones back in the world after you registered their position. So they won't clutter your inventory and you won't have to keep count if you find another of the same type.

Beside metal-type stones you should also pay attention to another two groups:
- Basalt, Komatite, Kimberlite (level 2)
- Red/Black Granite (level 3)

With three level 2 stones you can craft a better pickaxe. What you can or cannot harvest doesn't depend on the ore type, as in vanilla Minecraft, but on the rock layer you're mining.

Save Red or Black Granite for later, since with it you should craft a hammer instead of a pickaxe. Another quest down this path will explain how.

Death... isn't such a big deal.

Your items won't despawn because they should be safely stored in a gravestone, placed at the location of your death.

Sometimes the quality of a mod is in the small details.

While you've already used an axe, you probably don't know there are some options. The previous quest has already shown that by targeting the lowest wood block of a tree, you can harvest it all the way up. If you instead start from the topmost block, moving down, you can manually harvest single block by single block.

The durability loss is actually smaller if you harvest it block by block, but this still doesn't exhaust all options.

You can obtain some advantages by doing a bit more work: with a right click you can debark a single block of a tree. Doing this disables the possibility to auto-harvest, but the durability cost is decreased again, and the time is reduced.

More importantly, the de-barked wood you obtain this way is called "beam" and it produces three planks rather than the two from all other wood types.

The bark you obtain can be thrown in a furnace as fuel, and could be useful in a crucible.

You'll notice that the process is rather quick: debark and harvest the two blocks that are usually exposed at the bottom of a tree, then move right under the next block, and you can point and debark it from the bottom. As long the tree isn't very tall, this lets you harevest it quickly without bothering to remove the leaves.

(you can complete this quest with any type of beam)
